todied and authenticated through criome rather than borrowing the operator's logged-in session (GPG/SSH agent). Builds on agents holding cryptographic identity via criome.|] Medium Minimum Zero [lojix criome machine-identity])) (psc6 ([(Technology (Software (Security SecretsManagement))) (Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [The criome daemon holds an encrypted multi-key store: a master BLS keypair generated on first run, plus sub-keys. It always has a self-start key — the user home private key, the only one readable by the daemon/owning user, encrypted at rest with home-user or system encryption; other keys are sub-encrypted within the store. The secret never leaves criome; the owner can rotate on suspected leak. Transitional bootstrap until meta-signal-criome carries authenticated key config; hardware key mechanism is a later refinement.] Medium Minimum Zero [criome bls-key key-store meta-signal-criome])) (s8lq ([(Technology (Software (Security Authentication)))] Clarification [Browser automation for real user accounts should support attaching to a visible browser tab/session so the human can watch, intervene, and keep login/2FA secrets out of agent prompts and logs.] Medium Minimum Zero [browser-automation])) (cjrl ([(Technology (Software (Security SecretsManagement)))] Principle [|Secrets always land in the most secure store available: gopass (git-backed, encrypted) in the user session; SOPS-nix (encrypted at rest, decrypted only on target host at activation) for cluster deploy. Move secrets ciphertext-to-ciphertext, never through a visible intermediate. Agents may inspect plaintext only when a psyche/task-authorized job needs it; keep plaintext out of chat, reports, logs, commits, argv, shell traces, Nix store, fixtures, and checked-in files — prefer blind pipe-to-sink, else minimize exposure and move directly to the requested consumer/encrypted store. The local LLM API token installs via a command-backed gopass reference (e.g. Pi auth.j